Now impose that those who are asymptomatic are 25% less infective than clinical cases. Add the projected prevalence with those parameters to the previous graph.

In reality, most people do not become infectious right after they become infected. The period between the moment of infection and becoming infectious is typically referred to as the incubation period. Most models make the simplifying assumption that infectiousness starts on symptom presentation; thus the typical representation of the I class as reflecting both infectivity and symptomatology. In some cases, people can become infectious before they present with any symptoms. How would you incorporate such detail into the previous model? Draw the diagram below.


When adding an incubation or exposed compartment to a model, we need to decide what assumptions to make regarding: - Length of incubation period - Infectivity of incubation period


Explore ranges of both those parameters and write down your understanding of the relative importance of both to the observed dynamics. To add a bit more perspective, output the predicted final attack size (cumulative number of infections) for all explored parameter values.


Do this exploration systematically, by exploring all combinations of incubation period duration, v, and relative infectivity of asymptomatic infections, delta, given by the vectors:

v_vector<-seq(0.1,1,by=0.1)
delta_vector<-(seq(0.2,1,by=0.1))
result<-matrix(0,nrow = length(v_vector),length(delta_vector))

You should be able to generate a contour plot like the figure below

contour(result,xaxt = "n", yaxt = "n",xlab="v",ylab="delta",nlevels = 10, labcex=1.6,col = hcl.colors(12, "Temps"),lwd =2)
axis(1, at=1:length(v_vector)/length(v_vector), labels=v_vector)
axis(2, at=1:length(delta_vector)/length(delta_vector), labels=delta_vector)

Write down your understanding of these results.


Finally, consider a model with partial and temporary immunity. A generic framework that can be adopted to almost any infectious disease is illustrated below.

For the parameter set below explore the trade-off between infection and immunity loss.

parameters <- c(
  mu = (1/(50*52*7)),    
  beta = 0.25, 
  v = 1/4,
  gamma = 0.2,
  taua = 1/10,
  tauc = 1/10,
  phi = 0.05,
  rho = 1,
  sigma = 0.5,
  alpha = 1/180,
  delta_r = 0.0,
  delta=0.0
)

Do so by performing a sensitivity analysis, similar to the one above, over the following parameter space

beta_vector<-seq(0.1,3,by=0.2)
alpha_vector<-(seq(0.003,0.01,by=0.001))
result<-matrix(0,nrow = length(beta_vector),length(alpha_vector))

Interpret the results – you might remember a similar result presented in the paper we discussed 2 weeks ago (https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/16439331/). Note that in this case, the peak at intermediate beta values is not observed in clinical cases only, but in the overall number of cases. What do you think is responsible for such dynamics?
